**Section 1: User Story
**

**1.1** **Epic Story**

As an Advisory Notice (AN) Processing Officer who needs to follow up against ANs in the OCMS, I want the OCMS to process the ANs, so that appropriate follow-up action will be taken on the notices according to the automated processing workflow in Appendix B of Annex 1A.

**1.2 User Stories **

![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)
Note: URA will be omitting user story no. 10.3 for MVP1. 

**1.3 Key Functions &amp; Features**

| Functions | Description |
| --- | --- |
| Detecting ANs during Notice creation | New notices created in OCMS will be put through AN qualification check to verify whether the Notice is eligible for ANS or not. |
| Receiving ANs from Enforcement Systems | OCMS interfaces with REPCCS and CES to receive offence data for Notices which have been labelled as Advisory Notices by the Enforcement Systems. |
| Creating ANs from Staff Portals | OCMS also receives ANS which OICs create manually via the OCMS Staff Portal and PLUS Staff Portal. |
| Sending Advisory Notice eNotification (eAN) | OCMS sends an eNotification (eAN) to the Vehicle Owner to notify the Owner that an AN has been issued to the vehicle. An SMS will be sent if the Owner is an individual. An email will be sent if the Owner is a business entity. |
| Sending AN Letter | If OCMS is unable to send an eAN, it will proceed to generate a physical ANS Letter which will be mailed to the Vehicle Owner. |
| Suspending Notices with PS-ANS | OCMS suspends Notices with PS-ANS after: The eAN has been sent The ANS Letter has been dropped into the SFTP for the printing vendor |
| Reports for AN Notices and AN letters | OCMS generates two types of reports for ANS: Ad-hoc report for the number of AN Notices issued Reconciliation report for ANS letters |
| Sending Unqualified ANS to REPCCS and CES | OCMS sends a daily list of vehicle numbers that do not qualify for ANs to REPCCS and CES to support their enforcement actions. |

**Section 2: Advisory Notices**

**2.1** **Use case**

- Advisory Notices (AN) refer to Offence Notices which are not compoundable (payable) and will not be further processed.

- ANs are issued to Vehicle Owners in place of a parking fine and serve as formal warnings to notify them that they have committed an offence and to comply with Parking Rules.

- After a new Notice is created, OCMS uses the offence details to verify whether the Notice qualifies as an AN.

- AN verification is a process that consists of the following: Verifying whether the Notice meets the criteria that qualifies it as an AN. 

- Notices that qualify as AN will be updated with AN flag “Y” and redirected to the AN workflow where OCMS will send an eNotification (eAN) or a physical AN Letter to the Vehicle Owner to notify them of the AN.
- Notices will be permanently suspended with suspension code as ‘ANS’ after the e-notification or AN letter is sent out, i.e, PS-ANS.

For CES-sourced cases, OCMS sets the ANs flag directly from CES data and bypasses the ANs Qualification check . Where the ANS indicator is ‘Y’ from CES offence data , the notice shall be suspended with status PS-ANS immediately after creation . For non-CES sources, OCMS creates the notice with AN flag = ‘N’ and then the notice will go through the AN Qualification check to determine whether the notice should be treated as an ANs notice . |
| | Check for Double Booking | The system compares new notice details against existing notices to avoid issuing the same Notice twice. Compare new notice details against existing notices based on: Vehicle number Offence Date and time Computer Rule code Parking lot number (null = null) If the lot number from both notices are blank, they will be matched.) Car park code If the notice details are duplicated, the notice will be suspended as PS-DBB. |
| | | |
| | | |
| | | |
| 1 | AN Qualification | The AN Qualification check uses the following to determine whether: The Offence Rule Code is listed in the ANS Exemption List and is within the active exemption period. The vehicle has no past offence records The vehicle has one or more past Offence Notices created within the last 24 months from the current date, AND all past Offence Notices were suspended with ANS PS reason codes (CAN, CFA, DBB or VST). If the Notice meets the criterion for (a), the Notice does not qualify as an AN. If the Notice does not meet the criterion for (a) and meets the criteria under (b) or (c)the Notice qualifies as an AN. Note : The offence rule codes in the ANS Exemption table will be hardcoded. Any changes to this table will require users to submit a request to MGG for a patch update. |
| 2 | Update Notice as AN | Upon qualification, OCMS updates the Notice as an Advisory Notice (AN), so that it is not payable and it will be processed via the AN processing workflow, refer to Steps 4 to 9. If Notice does not qualifyfor AN after the checks, OCMS checks whether AN flag is ‘Y’ then update AN flag from Y to N. Notice will then continue along the standard Type O processing flow. |
| 4 | LTA Vehicle Ownership Check | OCMS submits the notice to LTA to retrieve the Vehicle Owner’s particulars. Note: For military vehicles (vehicle registration type “I”), system will bypass the LTA vehicle ownership check and use the MINDEF address in the database. |
| 5 | E-AN Qualification | OCMS performs the eNotification qualification check to determine whether to notify the Vehicle Owner via eNotification (SMS or email) or via a physical letter: If the Owner is eligible for eNotifications (eAN), OCMS proceeds to Steps 6a and 6b. If the Owner opted out of receiving eNotifications, OCMS proceeds to Steps 7a and 7b. |
| 6a | Query DataHive for Mobile Number or Email Address | OCMS queries DataHive to retrieve the following contact information: For individuals, OCMS uses the NRIC or FIN to retrieve the mobile number of the Owner For business entities, OCMS uses the UEN to retrieve the email address for the company that owns the vehicle If there is no contact number retrieved, OCMS proceeds to steps 7a and 7b. |
| 6b | Send eAN SMS or Email | OCMS proceeds to send an SMS or email to inform the Vehicle Owner of the AN. OCMS retries the sending later in the day if the initial send fails If eAN sending was not successful, OCMS will redirect the Notice to the physical letter flow in Steps 7a and 7b. If eAN sending was successful, OCMS proceeds to Step 8. |
| 7a | Query MHA and/or DataHive for Address | OCMS detects owner identification type before query the Owner’s latest registration address. (1) If the owner is NRIC, FIN and UEN holders, OCMS proceeds to query for Owners’ latest registered address. For NRIC holders, OCMS submits the NRIC number to MHA to retrieve the Owner’s latest’s registered address. For FIN and UEN holders, OCMS uses the FIN/UEN number to query DataHive to retrieve the Owner’s latest’s registered address. For Passport holder, OCMS uses the registered address returned by LTA. For military vehicles (vehicle registration type “I”), OCMS uses the MINDEF address in the database. |
| 7b | Generate AN Letter and Sent | OCMS proceeds to generate the AN letter using the latest registered address. OCMS submits the letter file to the Printer for printing and sending. OCMS continues to Step 8 thereafter. |
| 8 | Suspend Notice with PS-ANS | OCMS proceeds to suspend the Notice with PS-ANS to stop the Notice processing. |
| 9 | Send Daily List of Unqualified AN | OCMS sends an end-day file with the latest list of vehicle numbers that do not qualify for AN and sends the file to REPCCS and CES for use during enforcement. |
| 10 | End | The process concludes. |

**2.3** **AN Eligibility**

- An AN-eligible notice is a notice that meets the criteria in 2.3.1. 

- AN-eligible Notices are sent for AN qualification to determine whether they qualify as AN.

**2.3.1 Criteria for AN-eligible Notices **

- Parking Offences (Type O), Payment Evasion (Type E) , and 

- Vehicle Registration Types: ‘S’ – Local 
- ‘D’ – Diplomat
- ‘V’ – VIP 
- ‘I’ – Military
**2.3.2 Exclusions (Not eligible for AN) **

- Foreign vehicles (Vehicle Registration Type ‘F’ – Foreign)
- Payment Evasion offences (Type E)
- Unauthorised Parking Lots offences (Type U)

**2.4** **Attributes of an Advisory Notice**

- When a Notice qualifies as an AN, OCMS updates the Notice details in the databases to indicate that the Notice is an AN. 

- The following fields in the databases are updated: 

| Database Table | Field | Before AN Qualification | After AN Qualification |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| ocms_valid_offence_notice | an_flag | ‘N’ - No/’Y’ - Yes | ‘Y’ - Yes |
| ocms_valid_offence_notice | payment_acceptance_allowed | ‘Y’ - Yes | ‘N’ - No |
| ocms_valid_offence_notice | an_flag | N’ - No/ ‘Y’ - Yes | ‘Y’ - Yes |
| ocms_valid_offence_notice | payment_acceptance_allowed | ‘Y’ - Yes | ‘N’ - No |

- All other fields in the database tables listed above remain unchanged. 
*Note: ANS notices are not allowed for furnishing of hirer/driver in the e-service

- AN Notices can be identified by the AN Flag field located at the bottom right corner in the Overview tab in the View Notice screen

**Section 3: AN Verification**

**3.1** **Use case**

- OCMS performs a verification process to determine whether a Notice qualifies as an AN. 
- OCMS reviews the Offence Details to determine: Whether the Offence Rule Code of the new Notice is eligible for ANS, and/or 
- Whether the vehicle has any past offences in the last 24 months, and whether all past Notices were suspended with the following PS Suspension Codes:CAN
- CFA
- DBB
**3.2** **AN Qualification Check**

**3.2.1 Use Case **

- A Notice is sent for AN Qualification after the Same-Day AN check determines that it is eligible as an AN. 

- The objective of the AN Qualification check is to verify if the Notice qualifies as an AN.

- The AN Qualification process checks the Offence Rule Code and Vehicle Number of the new notice to determine that it qualifies as an AN: 
- The Offence Rule Code is not listed in the ANS exemption list, **OR** if the Offence Rule Code is listed, the offence date is not within the active exemption period and does not bear the specific rule remark and composition amount listed; **AND**The vehicle has no past Offences Notices created within the last 24 months from the current date **OR**
- The vehicle has one or more past Offence Notices created within the last 24 months from the current date, **AND** all past Offence Notices were suspended with ANS PS reason codes (CAN, CFA, DBB or VST).

**3.2.2 High Level Process Flow for AN Qualification **

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

NOTE: Due to page size limit, the full-sized image is appended.
![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)

| S/N | Process Name | Description of Process |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Start | The AN Qualification Process begins once a Notice has passed the Same-Day AN Check. |
| 2 | ANS Exemption Rule Code Check | OCMS checks if the Notice’s Offence Rule Code is exempt from (not eligible for) ANS by checking the New Notice’s Offence Rule Code against the ANS Exemption Rule database table. If the Notice’s Offence Rule Code is found in the ANS Exemption Rule database table, the Notice is not eligible for ANS. OCMS will stop the AN Qualification process and the Notice will continue to be processed along the standard Type O workflow. If the Notice’s Offence Rule Code is not listed in the ANS Exemption Rule database table, OCMS proceeds to Step 3 |
| 3 | Past Offences Check | OCMS checks whether the vehicle has committed offences in the past 24 months by querying the Valid Offence Notice database table: If the vehicle does not have any past Notice, the new Notice qualifies as an AN. OCMS then continues to Step 4. If there are Notices returned, OCMS proceeds to the next step to check whether all the past Notices were suspended with ANS PS Codes (CAN, CFA, DBB, VST): If all past Notices were suspended with ANS PS Codes, the new Notice qualifies as an AN. OCMS then continues to Step 4. If one or more past Notices were not suspended with ANS PS Codes, the new Notice does not qualify as an AN. OCMS will stop the AN Qualification process and the Notice will continue to be processed along the standard Type O workflow. |
| 4 | Update New Notice as an AN | If the new notice qualify as an AN, OCMS update the new notice as AN: (a) If AN_flag = ‘Y’, it remains unchanged. (b) If AN flag is ‘N’ or NULL, it set the AN flag to ‘Y’. (c) Payment_Acceptance flag to set to “N” Note: Furnishing of hirer/driver’s particulars in e-Service is also not allowed. |
| 5 | End | The Process concludes. |

**Section 4: Receiving AN Offence Data **

**4.1** **Use case**

- OCMS receives raw Offence data sent by the following backend enforcement systems for Notice creation and processing:REPCCS 
- CES 

- REPCCS and CES use the ANSFlag field to indicate whether the Notice is eligible as an AN. 

- While OCMS receives the ANS Flag indicator sent by CES, OCMS will set the ANs flag directly based on CES data and will not perform the ANs Qualification check. If the CES AN indicator = ‘Y’, the notice shall be created with ANs flag = ‘Y’ and subsequently suspended with status/reason PS-ANS.

- While OCMS receives the ANSFlag indicator sent by REPCCS, OCMS will not process the indicator value. It will disregard the indicator value sent by the backend enforcement systems. After AN qualification check for the notice, OCMS will update AN flag: IF AN flag is ‘Y’ and the notice is not eligible for ANS at time of checking in OCMS. OCMS will updated AN flag from ‘Y’ to ‘N’ and vice versa.
- IF AN flag is ‘Y’ and the notice is eligible for ANS, OCMS won’t update AN flag.
- OCMS will perform the AN Qualification processes for every Notice sent by REPCCS and other sources ( OCMS Staff Portal and PLUS Staff Portal ). 
**4.2** **Receiving eligible ANs from REPCCS**

**4.2.1 Interfacing with REPCCS to Receive Offence Data For New Notices**

- OCMS provides an API that allows REPCCS to send raw Offence data to OCMS. *Refer to Section 2 of the OCMS 3 Functional Document for the raw Offence data sent by REPCCS. [OCMS 3 v1.6]*

- When the API request is received, OCMS validates the data sent, including the ANSFlag indicator, to determine whether a new Notice can be created: If the raw Offence data does not meet the criteria for Notice creation, OCMS responds to REPCCS with an error message 
- If the raw Offence data meets the criteria for Notice creation, OCMS proceeds to create the new Notice. 
- *Refer to Section 4 of the OCMS 11 Functional Document [Pls indicate version number once finalised].
*
- After the new Notice is created, OCMS initiates the AN Verification Process to determine whether the Notice qualifies as an AN. 

**4.2.2 AN Verification **

- All new Notices sent by REPCCS will be put through the AN verification process described in Section 3 of this document to verify whether they qualify as an AN:If the Notice does not qualify, OCMS will continue to process the Notice along the standard Parking Offence (Type O) processing flow. *Refer to the OCMS 11 Functional Document [Pls indicate version number once finalised]. 
*
- If the Notice qualifies as an AN, OCMS proceeds to update the Notice as an AN and will process it along the AN processing flow. *Refer to Section 2 of this document.*
**4.2** **Receiving eligible ANs from CES**

**4.2.1 Interfacing with CES to Receive Offence Data For New Notices**

- OCMS provides an API that allows CES to send raw Offence data to OCMS. *Refer to Section 2.2.3 for the raw Offence data sent in OCMS 3.*

- When the API request is received, OCMS validates the data sent, including the ANSFlag indicator, to determine whether a new Notice can be created: If the raw Offence data does not meet the criteria for Notice creation, OCMS responds to CES with an error message 
- If the raw Offence data meets the criteria for Notice creation, OCMS proceeds to create the new Notice. 
- *Refer to Section 4 of the OCMS 11 Functional Document [Pls indicate version number once finalised].
*
- After the new Notice is created, OCMS initiates the AN Verification Process to determine whether the Notice qualifies as an AN. 

**4.2.2 AN Verification **

- All new Notices sent by CES will be put through the AN verification process described in Section 3 of this document to verify whether they qualify as an AN:If the Notice does not qualify, OCMS will continue to process the Notice along the standard Parking Offence (Type O) processing flow. *Refer to the OCMS 11 Functional Document [Pls indicate version number once finalised]. 
*
- If the Notice qualifies as an AN, OCMS proceeds to update the Notice as an AN and will process it along the AN processing flow. *Refer to Section 2 of this document.*

**Section 5: Retrieving Vehicle Owner Particulars for Advisory Notices**

**5.1** **Use case**

- An eNotification or a physical Advisory Notice Letter will be sent to Vehicle owners to notify them of the AN. 

- The process to determine whether to send an eNotification or physical letter involves:Retrieving the Vehicle Owner’s information from LTA 
- Detecting whether the Notice has been suspended 
- Detecting whether the Owner is in the eNotification Exclusion list 
- Following AN Verification, qualified ANs will be submitted to LTA to retrieve the Vehicle Owner information. If the vehicle is a military vehicle, the Owner is automatically identified as MINDEF and the Notice will not be sent to LTA for ownership checks.

- After receiving the Owner information from LTA and before sending e-notification, OCMS checks: Whether the Notice has been suspended - OCMS will halt AN processing for all suspended notices, except those suspended with TS-HST. 

- Whether the Owner is in the eNotification Exclusion list - If the Owner is listed, OCMS will send a physical AN letter.

- Whether the Owner’s registered ID type is Passport – If the Owner is a passport holder, OCMS will send a physical AN letter to the registered address returned by LTA.
- Whether the vehicle registration type is ‘V’ (VIP), ‘D’ (Diplomatic) or ‘I’ (Military) – If the Owner is one of these 3 types, OCMS will send a physical AN letter.
- To send an eNotification, OCMS queries DataHive to retrieve the mobile numbers of individuals or email addresses for business entities. 

- To send an AN Letter, OCMS queries MHA and/or DataHive (based on the Owner’s ID type) to retrieve the latest registered address.
**5.2** **LTA Vehicle Ownership Check**

**5.2.1 Use case **

- OCMS sends the vehicle number to LTA to retrieve the Owner’s ID number and particulars, so that OCMS can send e-notifications to the owner and continue to retrieve the Owner’s registered address in the subsequent processes. 
- After the LTA enquiry has been sent, the Notice enters the ROV processing stage to continue the next steps of processing:Await the ownership enquiry result and update the Owner’s particulars
- Identify the method of notifying the Owner of the AN
**5.2.2 Process Flow for LTA Ownership Check**

*Refer to the OCMS 7 Functional Document version 1.6 for details on Ownership enquiry and result processing.*

**5.2.3 Ownership Check Outcomes**

| Ownership Enquiry Result | Next Step | Impact to AN |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Owner particulars found | OCMS saves the Owner information to the database. | AN proceeds to MHA and/or DataHive enquiry for contact details and registered address. |
| Owner particulars not found (error code 1/2/3/4) | Notice is suspended with TS-ROV. TS-ROV will be re-applied after the TS revives and the Owner’s particulars are still unavailable during the subsequent ownership checks. | OCMS does not have Owner information to proceed to the next step in AN processing. Vehicle Owner will not be notified of the AN. |

**5.3** **E-AN Qualification to Determine Method for Notifying Vehicle Owner **

**5.3.1 Use case **

- OCMS has two ways of notifying vehicle owners of the AN – via SMS/email or via a physical letter. 

- OCMS runs a 2-step check to determine which method to use: OCMS checks the Owner’s ID number against the eNotification Exclusion List to determine whether the Owner has opted out of receiving electronic messages (SMS/email)

- OCMS also detects Owners who are listed as passport holders, VIP, DIP or MID. If the Owner is a passport holder, VIP, DIP or MID, OCMS route the Notice to the AN letter generation flow. 

**5.3.2 Process Flow to Determine Method for Notifying Vehicle Owner**

*Refer to the Section 6 of the OCMS 11 Functional Document for details on the steps to determine whether the Owner receives eNotifications at the ENA stage or the physical letter at the RD1 stage. [Pls indicate version number once finalised].*

**5.4** **Retrieving Vehicle Owner’s Mobile or Email Address for eNotifications**

**5.4.1 Use case **

- OCMS detects the Owner’s ID type to determine the data source to retrieve the Owner’s contact information. 

| Owner Type | Process | Data Source to Query |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Individual | Use Owner’s NRIC or FIN number to query DataHive for the Owner’s mobile number | DataHive Dataset ID = D75 Dataset table name = V_DH_SNDGO_SINGPASSCONTACT_MASTER |
| Business Entity (Company) | Use Owner’s UEN number to query DataHive for the Owner’s email address | DataHive Dataset ID = D37 Dataset table name = V_DH_CORPPASS_DELTA |

**5.4.2 Process Flow to Retrieve Vehicle Owner’s Mobile or Email **

*Refer to the Section 3 of the OCMS 9 Functional Document [Pls indicate version number once finalised]

***5.4.3 DataHive Check Outcomes**

| Ownership Enquiry Result | Next Step | Impact to AN |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Owner’s contact information is retrieved | OCMS saves the Owner information to the database. AN enters the ENA processing stage | AN is ready for eNotification SMS or email sending |
| Owner contact information is not found | OCMS changes the Next Processing Stage to RD1 and Next Processing Date to Next Day. AN will be scheduled for submission to MHA and/or DataHive for registered address retrieval | AN will be redirected to the AN Letter generation flow. |

**Section 6: Sending eNotifications for AN (eAN)**

**6.1** **Use case**

- OCMS eNotifications for Advisory Notices (eAN) are sent to Vehicle Owners via SMS or email to notify Owners of the Offences and inform them that they face penalties if they commit another offence. 

- If the Vehicle Owner is an individual, the eAN is sent as an SMS. 

- If the Vehicle Owner is a business entity, the eAN is sent as an email.

- In the event that the Vehicle Owner is not eligible to receive an eNotification, OCMS will send an AN Letter instead. Refer to Section 7 of this document. 
**6.2** **Process Flow**

- The process flow for sending the eAN is similar to the eNotifcation sending process for Parking Offence (Type O) Notices that is outlined in Section 7 of the OCMS 11 Functional Document on Parking Offence (Type O) Processing Workflow *[Pls indicate version number once finalised].*
- The key difference between Type O processing for an AN is: OCMS suspends the AN with PS-ANS after the eAN has been sent. 
- The process flow for sending eAN is managed by 2 scheduled cron processes: 

| Name of Cron | Description |
| --- | --- |
| eREMINDER SMS Email | This cron is scheduled to run at 10am. The cron consists of the following functions: Query DataHive for the Offender’s mobile number or email Generate the eNotication message Send the SMS/email eNotification Update the send status in the database |
| eREMINDER SMS Email Retry | This cron is scheduled to run at 2pm on the same day. The cron consists of the following functions: Query the database for SMSes/emails that encountered sending errors during the 10am cron run. Re-send the SMS/email eNotification Update the final send status in the database If the message still fails during the resend, OCMS updates the following attributes of the AN so that it can be redirected to the AN Letter processing workflow: Next Processing Stage is changed to RD1 Next Processing Date is changed to the next day |

**6.2.1 Process Flow for Sending eAN SMS and Email**

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

NOTE: Due to page size limit, the full-sized image is appended.

![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)

| S/N | Process Name | Description of Process |
| --- | --- | --- |
| | Pre-condition | Scheduled cron job runs daily at 1000hrs to prepare and send eAN SMSes and emails. Queries DB for notices and offender details Queries DB to confirm if eNA has been sent previously |
| 1 | Detect Offender ID Type | OCMS determines whether the offender ID belongs to an individual or a business entity. |
| 2 | Query DataHive | System queries DataHive to retrieve mobile number(s) and email address(es) of the Vehicle Owner. If the Owner’s contact information is not found, OCMS Updates the Notice details to change the Next Processing Stage to RD1 and Next Processing Date to the next day, so that the Notice is directed to the AN Letter generation workflow. If the Owner’s contact information is received, OCMS: Stores the Owner’s contact details in the ocms_offence_notice_owner_driver database. Moves the Notice into the ENA Processing Stage. Proceeds to Step 3 |
| 3 | Identify AN | System reads the Notice details in the ocms_valid_offence_notice database to detect the an_flag value. If an_flag = Y, OCMS proceeds to Step 4. If an_flag = N, OCMS will process the Notice as a standard eNotification for Reminders. |
| 4 | Retrieve AN Message Template | AN message template (SMS and email content) is retrieved. |
| 5 | Generate SMS &amp; Email | Notification messages are generated from the template. |
| 6 | Send SMS &amp; Email | Generated SMS and email are sent to the offender. If sending is successful, OCMS: Saves date sent, content and the status as “S” (Sent) Suspends the Notice with suspension type PS-ANS Updates the Suspension details in the database If sending fails, OCMS: Saves date sent, content, error message and the status as “E” (Error) in these data tables: ocms_sms_notification_records ocms_email_notification_records |
| 7 | Process All Records | The Cron runs until the send status for all records has been updated, and suspension for all successful records have been completed. |
| 8 | End | Cron job ends. |

**6.2.2 Process Flow for Resending eAN SMS and Email**

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

NOTE: Due to page size limit, the full-sized image is appended.

![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)

| S/N | Process Name | Description of Process |
| --- | --- | --- |
| | Pre-condition | Scheduled cron job runs daily at 1400hrs to retry sending failed eAN SMSes and emails. |
| 1 | Query DB for Failed Notifications | OCMS queries the following DB tables to retrieve records which failed sending during the 1000hr run: ocms_sms_notification_records ocms_email_notification_records |
| 2 | Retry Sending | System resends the failed SMS and email notifications. |
| 3 | Save Re-send Status | System records the outcome of the resend attempt. If resend is successful, OCMS: Updates the eNotification status in the database to “S” (Sent) Suspends the Notice with PS-ANS and the process ends Updates the Notice details to change the Next Processing Date to current day. If the resend is unsuccessful, OCMS: Re-updates the eNotification status in the database to “E” (Error) Updates the Notice details to change the Next Processing Stage to RD1 and Next Processing Date to the current day, so that the Notice is directed to the AN Letter generation workflow. |
| 4 | Process All Records | The Cron runs until the re-send status for all records has been updated, and the subsequent actions (suspend notice or patch to RD1) has been completed. |
| 5 | End | Cron job ends. |

**Section 7: Sending AN Letter**

**7.1** **Use case**

- OCMS sends the AN Letter to Vehicle Owners when any one of the following conditions is met: The Owner is listed in the eNotification Exclusion List database 
- The Owner’s contact information (mobile number or email address) cannot be retrieved from DataHive
- eNotification sending and the subsequent re-send failed
- Passport, VIP, diplomatic, military vehicle owners
**7.2** **Process Flow**

- The process flow for generating and sending the AN Letter is similar to that of Reminder Letters which is outlined in Section 7 and Section 8 of the OCMS 11 Functional Document on Parking Offence (Type O) Processing Workflow *[Pls indicate version number once finalised].*
- The key difference between Type O processing and AN processing is: OCMS suspends the AN with PS-ANS after the AN Letter has been sent to the printing vendor. 
- The process flow for generating and sending the AN Letter is managed by the Prepare for Reminder Letters cron which is also used to process Reminder Letters.

| Name of Cron | Description |
| --- | --- |
| Prepare for Reminder Letter cron | This cron is scheduled to run at the end of the day. The cron consists of the following functions: Query MHA and DataHive for the Offender’s latest registered address Generate the AN Letter Drop the letter file into the SFTP for the printing vendor Update the letter status in the database |

**7.2.1 Process Flow for AN Letter Generation**

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

NOTE: Due to page size limit, the full-sized image is appended.

![](data:image/x-emf;base64,)

| S/N | Process Name | Description of Process |
| --- | --- | --- |
| – | Pre-condition | Scheduled cron runs daily at the end of the day (eg. 0030hr) to prepare the Letter files for sending to the printing vendor. |
| 1 | Query Notices | OCMS queries the database to retrieve all Notices that require letter generation. |
| 2 | Detect Offender ID Type | OCMS identifies the Vehicle Owner’s ID type - FIN, or UEN to prepare to query DataHive and Vehicle Owner’s ID type is NRIC, prepare to query MHA. |
| 3 | Query MHA/DataHive | OCMS queries MHA or DataHive for the Owner’s latest registered address. If the address is not found, OCMS suspends the Notice with TS-NRO and continues to process the next record. If the address is found, OCMS proceeds to Step 4 |
| 4 | Store Contact Info | The Owner’s registered address details are stored in the database. |
| 5 | Identify AN | OCMS then determines whether the Notice is an Advisory Notice (AN). If the Notice is not an AN, the Notice continues along the Standard Reminder Letter generation flow. If the Notice is an AN, OCMS proceeds to step 6. |
| 6 | Retrieve AN letter template | OCMS queries the database to retrieve the AN Letter template to prepare for AN Letter generation and calculate the date of letter. |
| 7 | Generate AN Letters | OCMS proceeds to generate AN Letters in PDF format. |
| 8 | Encrypt AN Letter Files | OCMS proceeds to encrypt the AN Letter files. |
| 9 | Consolidate Letter Files and upload to Blob | OCMS consolidates all AN and Reminder Letter files and upload them to the Blob file storage. |
| 10 | Generate Control Summary | OCMS proceeds to generate the control summary report for Reminder Letters and AN Letters |
| 11 | Encrypt Control Summary | OCMS proceeds to encrypt the Control Summary Report |
| 12 | Upload Control Summary to Blob | The encrypted Control Summary Report is uploaded to Blob storage. |
| 13 | Consolidate for Printing Vendor | All encrypted files (Letters and Control Summary Report) are consolidated for delivery to the SFTP. |
| 14 | Drop Files to SFTP | The consolidated files are dropped into SFTP for the printing vendor. |
| 15 | Create Letter Records in Database and Complete Processing | For AN Notices, OCMS updates the new AN Letters database table to record the AN Letters. After which, OCMS suspends the AN Notice with PS-ANS to stop Notice processing. Afterward, OCMS updates the next processing date to the current date. For Reminder Notices, OCMS updates the RDP and DN database tables to record the Reminder Letters. After which, OCMS moves the Notices into the Next Processing Stage. |
| 16 | End | Cron job ends. |

**Section 8: Suspending Notices with PS-ANS**

**8.1** **Use case**

- OCMS automatically suspends AN Notices with PS-ANS after the following processing steps are completed: The eAN eNotification has been sent successfully to the Vehicle Owner
- The AN Letter has been deposited into the SFTP for the printing vendor 
- OCMS OICs can also manually suspend Notices with PS-ANS via the OCMS Staff Portal. 
- The PS-ANS suspension indicates that OCMS will no longer process the AN. 
- Refer to Section 2 of the OCMS 18 Functional Document *[Pls indicate version number once finalised].

**Section 10: Sending Unqualified AN to REPCCS and CES**

**10.1** **Use Case**

- OCMS sends a list of vehicle numbers that do not qualify for ANS to REPCCS and CES so that their systems can use the list to decide whether a vehicle is eligible for AN. 

- The list is sent to REPCCS and CES at a scheduled time via SFTP file daily.
- Refer to Section 6 of the OCMS 2 Functional Document for the specifications of the interfacing with REPCCS. 
- The interface with CES is a new requirement/scope for OCMS 2 and will be based on the specifications for REPCCS.
